MISSING: Luis Davila (31 years old at the time of his disappearance), is from Bentonville, Arkansas, and was in Mexico visiting his girlfriend near Monterrey. Luis was last seen near Monterrey, Mexico, on March 29, 2021, wearing a white shirt and jeans. He was driving a silver 2016 Nissan Maxima (Arkansas License Plate 936-VET). Although the whereabouts of Luis are unknown at this time, it is believed he may still be in Mexico, possibly near Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas. Luis may be the victim of a kidnapping. A 44-year-old man was taken into custody a month after a woman was found chained up inside an abandoned home on the cityâ€™s South Side.

The Chicago Police Department announced #JoelCammon was located and arrested June 21 by members of the department as well as the U.S. Marshals Great Lakes Regional Fugitive Task Force on the 11800 block of South Central Avenue in Alsip, Illinois.

Police say he was identified as the man who allegedly kidnapped and sexually assaulted a 36-year-old woman between May 18 and May 21 inside an abandoned home on the 11900 block of South Eggleston.

A good Samaritan was walking down Eggleston on May 21 when he reportedly heard screams for help. According to WGN-TV, the victim, who remained unidentified, said she had been raped twice.

She reportedly told WGN, "He left me there handcuffed and chained."

Cammon was booked into the Cook County Jail on charges of aggravated kidnapping and aggravated criminal sexual assault.

Thank you to @authorjamiller and @bythebookvbp for my ARC. Holy plot twist at the end of this book!! The Drop has extremely short chapters and it's almost jarring at first, but made for a quick read and upped the ante to really make you feel how quickly everything was happening. 

I liked Ariana and Jimmy a lot, but wish Rafael had turned out to be a more level headed, honorable man. I guess after everything he went through that's not entirely realistic. 

I loved the setting in Cuba and wish we had even more description of Havana and the culture. While I knew about the historical significance of the dates I'm glad the epilogue re-inforced how close to the revolution this book was set and I think that definitely added to the overall urgency of the story for me.

Synopsis:

Havana, Cuba: 1958

	Ariana Rojas is alluring, intelligent, sophisticated, and wealthy â€“ at least until a brutal dictator steals the family fortune. Determined to get back what she lost, she joins the revolution, taking a job as a maid at the Paradise Hotel and Casino â€“ just to make ends meet. It isnâ€™t long before she hatches a clever scheme, the perfect crime, to recover what she once had while getting revenge at the same time.

	Jimmy Foster is a wealthy American who spends weekends in Havana with his gorgeous wife Darlene. They befriend the casino manager, a mobster named Buddy Stefano, except Darlene becomes a little too friendly. Buddy, a loyal member of the Mafia, sends a briefcase full of money back to his mob bosses in the States every month. 

 Ariana finds out about the briefcase and, with help from her revolutionary friends, breaks into Stefanoâ€™s safe and steals it, finding a hundred thousand dollars in cash inside. But the money isnâ€™t enough â€“ not for all she has planned. So she kidnaps Jimmy Foster.

	Harry Bennett is a mysterious man with a unique talent. He makes people disappear â€“ in more ways than one. He could be a detective, FBI, Cuban police, an insurance investigator â€“ no one knows for sure. But he finds a trail to Jimmy Foster.

Bandits assassinate lecturer at Zamfara State's Abdu Gusau Polytechnic, after duping his family into paying a massive ransom

According to reports, the deceased, Sanusi Halilu Kaura, was taken more than a month ago while traveling to Abuja for the NYSC mobilization of polytechnic students on the Kaduna-Abuja route.

The terrorists were alleged to have sought a five million naira ransom for the academician's release, which was paid by his family.

He claimed that the bandits informed the family that Kaura had been slain shortly afterwards. According to reports, the finding suggests that the terrorists murdered Kaura long ago, even as discussions for his release were ongoing.

So firstly, I absolutely LOVED the ending of this book. It slotted all lose ends in a tiny little perfect book conclusion bow. But, it is most likely not a book I'd re-read, I would however read a spin off or a second book. 

 The spiciness between Sloan and Lincoln is to die for. While I was a little turned off by the way Lincoln originally treated Sloan and how quick of a flip he made, in the end it was worth it. 

I also really disliked the detective skills Sloan shown, she was supposed to be a bit shot Detective, but in all honesty she was pretty shitty at her job. Her being a great detective wouldn't have hurt the storyline nor her being distracted occasionally by Lincoln. I know that the Police Dept . Was known to be slow and incompetent, but it almost seemed like she wasn't trying AT ALL to solve the murders. There were things super obvious that she as a detective, I believe should have picked up on, without giving away to early who the serial killer was. 

On that note, I guessed who the serial killer was VERY VERY VERY VERY early on... Like first couple chapters figured it out... It wasnt that difficult, even though I didn't know the motive until way later. 

I also figured out the second plot twist very early on as well, which was a tad disappointing. 

One thing that bothered me tremendously, is that at the beginning it mentioned Sloan being kidnapped and held captive by a serial killer and then rescued by her partner Alex, but it NEVER mentions it again... Ever. So it was pretty pointless to have it in the book at all in my opinion. It had zero connection to the remainder of the book. 

I did very much enjoy the love and connection between Lincoln and Sloan though. Even if he was a complete douche at first. 

I would recommend this book to others who love mystery mixed in with romance and a tad smut ğŸ˜‰ğŸ˜‰
